d linguistically. Its modernized and annotated edition in the original Spanish with an admirably readable English translation on facing pages will have significant impact on the study ofSpanish Peninsular and Sephardic literatures and cultures, and on early modern gender studies, linguistics, and comparative literature. ENRIQUETA ZAFRA is Assistant Professor of Spanish at Trent University. ANNEJ. CRUZ is Professor of Spanish and Cooper Fellow at the University of Miami.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBrothelsvFictionzSpain. 0aProstitutionvFictionzSpain. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh1 aCruz, Anne J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Anne J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZafra, Enriqueta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZafra, Enriqueta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846159404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846159404/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles